IS  - NA
AB  - The Cocos (Keeling) Islands are characterised by a fringing coral reef surrounded by deep water. Its Indian Ocean location as well as its low-lying topography, vulnerability to coastal hazard and the potential impacts of climate change is perhaps the most critical issue affecting island inhabitancy. To aid planning, a coastal vulnerability assessment of the southern atoll is being undertaken, including a 12-months metocean monitoring campaign. In this study, wave and water level measurements over a 17-week period were analysed to assess wave transformation and wave-driven set-up over the fringing reef. Assessing the wave transformation showed that, in agreement with literature, a shift from incident swell waves to lower amplitude infragravity waves occurs across the coastal profile. The infragravity waves propagate over the shallow reef flat and significantly contribute to wave-driven set-up near the shore. Wave-driven set-up reached 0.6m due to infragravity waves during periods of high-energy incident swell conditions and accounted for 64% of the nearshore non-tidal sea level variation during the deployment period. The analyses undertaken herein will improve the understanding of the metocean conditions contributing to coastal change at Cocos and support the verification/calibration of numerical models supporting the coastal vulnerability assessment and the prediction of inundation risk. Â© Australasian Coasts and Ports 2019 Conference. All rights reserved.
