AB  - India's ocean policy in the Indian Ocean has been under strain both from within and outside the country. It is argued that India's imperatives as the first pioneer investor have to be analyzed in the light of its growing interest in the areas of deep-sea mining, pelagic fisheries, sea farming, offshore engineering, underwater technology, and coastal zone management. There is a need to adopt an integrated marine policy, despite the difficulties inherent in its conception. Joint management of resources could enable disputed zones to be developed, and joint naval patrols could be symbolic of mutual trust and cooperation in protecting EEZ (exclusive economic zone) rights at the regional level. The complex intertwining of questions concerning the new International Law of the Sea and the coastal political geography of South Asia has added to the existing discord and divergence. It is concluded that the time is ripe to establish a certain broad relationship among national and naval power, EEZ size, and the nature of extraregional interference. India's overall geostrategic context justifies a navy with necessary substance for a forward defense strategy. The concept of an Indian Ocean Zone of Peace still has much support, but the political orientation of the proposal remains a divisive force.
