AB  - Global sea-level rise is seen as one of the most significant impacts of human-induced climate change, and is expected to affect coastal areas worldwide in the next 10 to 100 years. The coastlines of the Mediterranean Sea and Black Sea represent a critical hotspot, in this global scenario, due to high residential density, abundance of historical and cultural sites, variety and economic weight of maritime activities. Being semi-enclosed water bodies, these seas offer an almost unique opportunity to study possible remediation based on environmental engineering at the basin scale. A possible, albeit controversial, proposal is that of a barrage in the Strait of Gibraltar, to provide long-term protection at an affordable cost. The dam would be designed to initially cause a height difference between its two sides of about a metre, and allow inflow of Atlantic water to balance net evaporation. Aside from the need for shipping to pass through locks both at Gibraltar and Suez, adverse effects would include a rise in salinity, changes in nutrient cycling and biological impacts. Mitigation would require pumping out large volumes of Mediterranean deep water, over or through the dam. In addition to coastal protection, the dam would allow power generation and a land link between Europe and Africa. As planning and construction of the dam would require international agreements and resources, discussions should start about options and costs.
