AB  - Japan is a small county with only about 30 percent of available land suitable for urban development. Since its exclusive 200 nautical mile economic zone is about twelve times its land area, the effective use of this sea area is an important task. One concept for utilizing this area is the offshore man-made island. The construction of an offshore man-made island not only creates new land to meet social needs, but can also create a social foundation which gives rise to new social needs. In addition, the creation of a man-made structure in the sea can improve the marine environment and provide marine life with an enhanced and expanded habitat After briefly covering Japan's history of landfill projects, this paper will provide a definition of the concept of offshore man-made islands; the social background to their initial construction; and describe the roles and effects of offshore man-made islands in the social system. A special emphasis wild be placed on the role of offshore man-made islands as final landfills for urban waste, which is a major problem among advanced countries. This paper will also discuss technological problems by introducing actual case studies. Finally, this paper will determine that offshore man-made islands provide sustainable development benefitting the marine environment and the social system.
