AB  - A particular living area in the north part of Semarang has been renowned for its improper environmental conditions due to intensively increasing sea water tide overflow (inundation) every year. Many buildings do not meet the lowest standards of appropriate living place. Due to the salinity of sea water overflowing to the area, metal and electronic appliances are easily damaged. Regardless of this condition, occupants of the living area prefer to stay. This paper aims at explaining how occupants of the living area in the north part of Semarang city respond to the degradation of the living environment due to inundation. To gain the knowledge of the occupants' response towards the continuous degradation of their living environment, comprehensive interviews were undertaken. In addition, questionnaires were deployed to collect data on factors that influence the occupants to take adaptive actions; these data were analysed quantitatively. A survey was carried out by visually observing morphological changes in the surrounding environment. The changes were recorded ethnographically through a track record by interviews involving sketch/imaging tools. Ultimately, we provide an explanation of our observations based on responses and their influencing factors from the occupants in living environment with deteriorating conditions (inundation).
