IS  - NA
AB  - Low-lying, Pacific island nations face real and present threats from climate change in terms of loss of life, displacement of comunities as well as damage to public and private infrastructure. With the effects of sea level rise already being felt and at a high exposure to the seasonal passage of cyclones, protecting coastal communities and essential transport networks from inundation is vital to these developing nations future. The Asian Development Bank through its Climate Resilience Sector Project aims to mainstream climate resilience into government planning and address country priorities focusing on the most vulnerable sectors and communities. This paper details the key lessons learnt in the scoping, prioritisation, detailed design, procurement and construction of coastal defenses along the Hahake (East) coast of Tongatapu, the largest and most populated island of the Kingdom of Tonga. The Hahake coast is a â€œtropical reef-mediated systemâ€; meaning it's shoreline is sustained by and protected by a living reef ecosystem. Any change to the biological, chemical or physical composition of the system will change the sediment production and/or transport regimes and affect shoreline processes. Sea level rise and the passage of tropical cyclones is causing erosion along this coast and placing infrastructure at risk. Development of an appropriate design and construction methodology, utilising local material, plant and labour required an innovative and collaborative approach. In addition, extensive stakeholder consultation with both communities and governmental bodies revealed that coastal engineering practices applied in small island developing nations is not always consistent as community expectation, cultural sensitivities and subsistence priorities differ. Â© Australasian Coasts and Ports 2019 Conference. All rights reserved.
