AB  - This work describes the implementation of learning activities using ICT and digital skills and reflects on the potential and limitations of these experiences in citizen science projects. In a climate change scenario, the project ``EDUMAR - Educating for the Sea{''} aims to educate for the preservation and sustainability of the sea and its resources through citizen science. More than 300 primary school students participated in interdisciplinary science activities focusing on the causes and consequences of climate change in ecosystems of the intertidal rocky shores, learning to identify marine species and acquiring ICT skills to insert data in a biodiversity recording platform using a mobile application. The project also involved the participation of pre-service and in-service teachers, as well as researchers. Two main activities were conducted using ICT skills. First, students went to the National Museum of Natural History and Science (University of Lisbon), where researchers introduced: concepts related to climate change and its effect on biodiversity, practical activities on species identification, and the functioning of the Biodiversity4All/iNaturalist application. Secondly, students went to the Avencas beach (Portugal), and using the iNaturalist app, recorded the targeted species. They worked in groups of 5 students maximum and used a tablet to take pictures of intertidal marine species and uploaded them using the app. Methodology included the analysis of data inserted by children in the iNaturalist app, questionnaires to in-service teachers and focus group interviews with the research team. Results of data inserted in the platform enabled to access primary school students learning on species identification (around 46\% of the identifications were correct). Researchers and teachers' reflections were analysed and provided insights on several categories: students' motivation and autonomy, students' digital skills, tablet usability, friendly use of the iNaturalist app and limitations of the equipment, such as, tablet hardware characteristics with implications on image quality and app running performance, especially on saving data. Alongside the impact on students learning and ICT skills development, the activity also involved children in citizen science practices contributing to help scientists monitoring the coastal marine biodiversity and understanding how climate change may affect that biodiversity.
