AB  - With the closure of the Dutch estuary ``South Sea{''} in 1932, a large artificial lake was created of which the water level is controlled by discharge sluices. Due to a gradually rising sea level, the discharge capacity of these facilities has decreased and the control of the lake levels is insufficient. Future projections of sea level rise and rainfall patterns are highly uncertain, coupled to the uncertainties of climate change. Options for expanding discharge capacity were studied, using lifecycle costing. It could be shown that adaptive solutions are the most robust in view of the uncertain projections of the future. Lifecycle costing in the presented form turned out to be a suitable way of supporting public decision-making on large infrastructure.
