AB  - A consideration of coastal erosion in northeast Norfolk focusses attention on several issues. Subaerial processes, working on weak glacial deposits, lead to cliff instability, and to dramatic cliff falls, especially after heavy rain. These mass movements provide the major input to a system of sediment transfer to the southeast, which is of crucial importance in maintaining beach levels in the area downdrift. These beaches in turn provide the most effective means of dissipating wave energy, and provide a defence mechanism for the cliff itself. Human activity through time, however, has intervened in this system, and reduced the level of sediment movement, to preserve beaches at source. This article asks whether coastal erosion really is a problem and whether high-cost engineering works can provide a solution. -from Author
