AB  - In light of current predictions regarding climate change and its likely impacts on the coastal zone, maintaining and protecting the health and stability of developed coastal foreshores are a key priority for coastal local governments. Coastal foreshores characterise communities and provide major economic inputs through a myriad of commercial and recreational means. The diverse values of developed coastal foreshores are unquestioned; however, planning to adequately protect and adapt these areas is becoming increasingly complex, especially when considering the impacts of climate change. Rising sea levels, changing weather patterns and the increasing occurrence of severe storm events pose serious challenges for effective foreshore protection, particularly for existing coastal developments. The recent introduction of the Queensland Coastal Plan 2012 (the Coastal Plan) aimed to improve management and protection of environmental, economic and social coastal resources and considers the threats posed by changing climatic conditions and coastal processes. This intent was generally supported although, in practice, the Coastal Plan introduced significant constraints on coastal development and land use planning. Subsequent amendments to Queensland coastal policy have streamlined processes for coastal approvals and land use planning, which has improved certainty for local governments. The accretion and erosion of State coastal policies of the past two years have created challenges for local governments, particularly relating to the protection and adaptation of foreshore areas against the impacts of current and future coastal hazards. This paper examines the changes to Queensland coastal policies over the past two years. It also presents a case study detailing how Moreton Bay Regional Council (MBRC) has undertaken significant foreshore protection works in light of changes to coastal policy. The works incorporate a diverse range of foreshore protection and adaptation measures along five separate beach compartments spanning 6 km of the Redcliffe Peninsula. Successfully undertaking these works presented unique challenges for MBRC from a coastal approvals perspective.
